"Abstract Directory information is the customer information held by telecommunications companies. It is used to produce printed phone books and provide directory enquiries services as well as CD-ROMs and on-line non-operator assisted directory enquiries services. The telecommunications industry derives a direct benefit from the use of directory information services and products which generate revenue from the follow-on calls that are made as a result of successful directory searches. OFTEL has produced a Consultation Paper entitled Provision of Directory Information Services and Products which contains a detailed review of the current provision of directory information services and products to customers and makes extensive proposals for the liberalization of the directory enquiries market. The consultation process was completed early this year and the aim is to implement agreed changes as soon as possible in order to maximize customer benefit. However, as the implementation of some of the proposals would require operators to make system changes it may be some time before we see the full effect of the new-look directory enquiries market and OFTEL has invited operators to provide an indication of reasonable timescales for the implementation of such changes. This article looks at OFTEL's principal proposals, their practical effect and the legislative framework in which the directory enquiries market operates."
